# Environment Variables Configuration
# Copy this file to .env and update with your values

# Flask Configuration
SECRET_KEY=your-secret-key-here

# Database Configuration (SQL Server)
# Choose one of the following configurations:

# Option 1: SQL Server Express (most common for development)
DB_HOST=localhost\SQLEXPRESS
DB_NAME=todo_app_db
DB_DRIVER=ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server

# Option 2: SQL Server Standard/Enterprise
# DB_HOST=localhost
# DB_NAME=todo_app_db
# DB_DRIVER=ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server

# Option 3: Named SQL Server instance
# DB_HOST=localhost\SQL2019
# DB_NAME=todo_app_db
# DB_DRIVER=ODBC Driver 18 for SQL Server

# Option 4: Remote SQL Server
# DB_HOST=your-server-name.database.windows.net
# DB_NAME=todo_app_db
# DB_DRIVER=ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server

# Alternative: SQLite (for development)
# Comment out all SQL Server variables above to use SQLite
# The app will automatically fallback to SQLite if SQL Server variables are not set

# =============================================
# Quick Setup Instructions
# =============================================
# 1. Install SQL Server (if not already installed)
# 2. Open SQL Server Management Studio
# 3. Run the schema.sql file (src/database/schema.sql)
# 4. Install Python dependencies: pip install -r requirements.txt
# 5. Install SQL Server driver: pip install pyodbc
# 6. Copy this file to .env and update DB_HOST if needed
# 7. Run: python main.py

# =============================================
# Database Connection Details
# =============================================
# - DB_HOST: Your SQL Server instance name
#   * localhost\SQLEXPRESS (default Express edition)
#   * localhost (default instance)
#   * SERVER-NAME\INSTANCE (named instance)
#   * server.database.windows.net (Azure SQL)
# - DB_NAME: todo_app_db (created by schema.sql)
# - DB_DRIVER: ODBC driver installed on your system
#   * Check installed drivers: ODBC Data Source Administrator → Drivers tab

# =============================================
# Troubleshooting
# =============================================
# If you get connection errors:
# 1. Verify SQL Server is running
# 2. Check Windows Firewall allows SQL Server connections
# 3. Verify the ODBC driver name matches your installed version
# 4. For Express edition, enable TCP/IP in SQL Server Configuration Manager
# 5. Make sure your Windows user has SQL Server login permissions

# Common ODBC Driver Names:
# - "ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server" (recommended)
# - "ODBC Driver 18 for SQL Server" (newer)
# - "SQL Server" (older)
